I can find the SSH command for my private key in thr EC2 console under the "Connect" section of the instance details. 
It will look something like this: ssh -i /path/to/my-key.pem ec2-user@<public-ip-address>

Connect using a Public IP address is for public subnets, and allows direct access to the instance from the Internet
Connect using a Private IP address is for private subnets, and requires a VPN or Direct Connect connection to the VPC

From the console line you can use commands like ls, ifconfig and ping google.com to verify connectivity 
and check the instance's network configuration. You can also use the AWS CLI to manage your EC2 instances, 
such as starting, stopping, and terminating instances, as well as creating and managing EBS volumes and ENIs.

Remember to terminatet instances when you are done to avoid unnecessary costs, 
and to detach and delete any EBS volumes that are no longer needed.

Instance Metadata is data about the instance that can be accessed from within the instance itself
    - curl http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data to access instance metadata
    - curl http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/local-ipv4 to get the private IP address of the instance
    - curl http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/public-ipv4 to get the public IP address of the instance

IMDSv1 vs IMDSv2 (Instance Metadata Service):
    - IMDSv1: The original version, older and less secure
    - IMDSv2: The newer version, more secure, requires session tokens for authorization, 
              and is recommended for all new applications

Default is IMDSv1, but some instances might disable it as a default option, so 
it's important to check the instance metadata options when launching an instance.

